               <physDesc>
                  <objectDesc>
                     <supportDesc material="parchment">
                        <support>
                           <p>Parchment</p>
                        </support>
                        <extent>460 folios (ii+460+i)
                           
                        </extent>
                        <collation>
                           <p>
                           Extant quires are mostly of 8 leaves each.
                           Quires marked by decorative catchwords on the last page, but only few
                              of them have been preserved. 
                        </p>
                        </collation>
                     </supportDesc>
                     <layoutDesc>
                        <layout>
                           <p>Columns: 3;
                                                  ruled lines: 29;
                                                  written lines: 28; Uniform layout. Visible pricking and page by page plummet ruling. Graphic fillers at the end of the lines. Large square initial words. Last line of text written within ruling. Each of the books of the Pentateuch commences a new leaf and Hafṭarot
                              begin a new column.The beginning of each pericope marked by פ פ פ. </p>
                        </layout>
                     </layoutDesc>
                  </objectDesc>
                  <scriptDesc>
                     <scriptNote>Ashkenazi square script of the 14th century. Shimshon ben Ya῾aḳov Vivant: inscribed as the main
                        scribe in the colophon, folio 460v. Shelomoh ha-Naḳdan: inscribed as the punctuator in the colophon
                        on folio 460v. </scriptNote>
                  </scriptDesc>
                  <bindingDesc>
                     <binding>
                        <p> Pre-1600. Thick brown leather, blind tooled boards, with bosses.
                           Embroidered velour doublures. Boxed.  Spine: Biblia Hebraica. Mus. Brit. Jure Emptionis. 10,455. Plut.</p>
                     </binding>
                  </bindingDesc>
